evels, saving the CtpA information for speaker notes instead.\n\nI'm considering a few title options that emphasize the transcript-protein mismatch, settling on something like \"Lpt transcript maintained and upregulated; LptD/LptE protein decline reveals Layer 3 tension\" to capture the core finding.\n\nFor the speaker notes, I need to preserve the comprehensive original content but adjust it to reflect that this is now a data figure with the table demoted to the caption or footer, and clarify where the pilot and CtpA details will appear.\n\nThe in-place conversion approach makes sense here—converting slide 17 to a data figure with the heatmap while moving the pilot data to speaker notes. The missing pilots slide that the substory plan intended can be added separately by the orchestrator.\n\nNow I'm structuring the revised slide JSON with the heatmap figure, updated title reflecting the Lpt apparatus findings, and a detailed caption capturing the transcript-level changes and protein discordance. I'm refining the caption text for the heatmap figure, checking the character count to ensure it fits the constraints while capturing the key findings about the Lpt protein expression patterns and the discordance between transcript and proteome data. Continuing to count character positions through the string, tracking the cumulative offset as I move through more tokens and spaces. Continuing to parse character sequences and their positions...\n\nchecking the total comes to 241 characters, which stays comfortably under both the advisory and hard limits. Now I'm evaluating the title \"Lpt apparatus maintained at transcript; LptD/LptE protein decline reveals Layer 3 tension\" and starting to count its characters. Now I'm calculating the character count for the title and confirming it's within limits. I need to write out the full speaker notes, condensing the original content while incorporating the pilot and CtpA details—covering what the heatmap displays, the two upregulated transcript components with their fold changes and FDR values, the protein discordance findings, and the pilot transcript data. At the protein level, LptD and LptE both decline despite stable or elevated transcripts — a discordance I'm marking as unresolved since single-replicate proteomics can't distinguish between substrate limitation and active downregulation. There are also pilot-stage signals like lptC2 showing transcript downregulation but protein upregulation that need replication to confirm. Checking the output path is absolute and the slide metadata matches the original, then verifying that the revised content addresses the finding by converting the data table to the NB04 heatmap figure as requested, and confirming all numbers and citations trace back to the REPORT sections. The caption fits within the character limit, and the figure path checks out. The layout is shifting from data_table to data_figure, which means I need to verify the schema still aligns—title, figure, caption, and data_source are all accounted for. No new citations are being added, just the existing REPORT §Finding 4 reference. I'm noticing the original slide doesn't have an evidence_anchors field, but the output schema expects one, so I should include it. Writing the revised slide JSON... The proteome data reveals a discordance: LptD and LptE proteins are both downregulated despite stable or elevated transcripts, suggesting either substrate limitation or active turnover rather than transcriptional control. A pilot signal in lptC2 shows transcript decline but protein elevation, adding another layer of complexity that the single-replicate proteomics can't fully resolve. I'm reorganizing the figure layout to swap the data table for a heatmap visualization, reframing the narrative around the A14/A15 transcript-protein discordance while moving the pilot findings to speaker notes. Now I'm verifying the caption length for the Lpt CPM heatmap, which shows the upregulation of MsbA-like and LptC-related proteins at the transcript level against the downregulation of LptD and LptE proteins. Verifying character counts for each segment... I'm working through the character count for this proteomics data string, tracking the discrepancy between my manual count and the actual length, noting that the outer membrane proteome shows unresolved differences between transcript and protein levels. Continuing to count character lengths for the remaining genes and their associated data points, tracking the FDR values and fold changes for LptC-related and LptD entries. Continuing to add up the running total through the rest of the character counts. I'm verifying the character count is under 250 and checking that each finding in my revision matches what's documented in the report, starting with the MsbA-like and LptC-related entries. CCNA_01217 protein +0.77/+0.74 checks out in the report, and CtpA was correctly rejected due to insufficient FDR significance. All the numbers validate against the source document. Now I'm considering whether the substory_arc guidance about position-only changes should restrict me from doing a layout conversion, but I think the intent is really about reordering rather than restructuring the content itself.\n\nSince the finding explicitly identifies the issue as the wrong layout type—data_table instead of data_figure—and the fix hint suggests an in-place conversion, I'll move forward with the revision. Let me also verify the speaker_notes_seed is within the target length of 50-200 words, which should cover the heatmap visualization and the key transcript-level findings about the Lpt components.\n\nNow looking at the proteome data: there's a discordance between transcript and protein levels for the canonical Lpt machinery. LptD and LptE both show protein-level declines despite stable or elevated transcripts, which could reflect substrate limitation or active turnover in the absence of LPS. The single-replicate proteomics can't definitively distinguish between these mechanisms, so this registers as discordant rather than passing validation. There's also an interesting signal in lptC2 showing transcript downregulation but protein upregulation, suggesting post-transcriptional regulation at play.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6804,"cache_read_input_tokens":42340,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6804},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ba2d6b0f-241e-4c07-96a3-a6effebadbb7","uuid":"4b2dd071-09e2-4c53-8bb9-c76a2ecb77ee"}
